VALUES
(44, 1, 1, 42, 1, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection Between Theophilus References', 'Both passages address Theophilus directly, indicating a shared audience. This connection highlights the continuity in the narrative from Jesus'' teachings to the actions recorded in Acts.', 'theme', 0.524, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 1, 42, 24, 19, 19, 'both to do and teach', 'Connection of Jesus'' Deeds and Teachings', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' actions and teachings. Acts 1:1 refers to what Jesus began to do and teach, while Luke 24:19 describes Him as mighty in deed and word, highlighting His impactful ministry.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 1, 40, 4, 23, 24, 'began both to do and teach', 'Connection of Jesus'' Actions', 'This connection highlights what Jesus began both to do and teach, as seen in Acts 1:1, and is exemplified in Matthew 4:23-24, where Jesus is actively teaching and healing. Both passages emphasize the actions of Jesus in His ministry.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 1, 40, 11, 5, 5, 'all that Jesus began both to do', 'Connection of Jesus'' Works', 'Both passages emphasize the actions of Jesus in healing and teaching. Acts 1:1 refers to what Jesus began to do, while Matthew 11:5 lists specific miracles and teachings he performed.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 1, 43, 10, 32, 38, 'all that Jesus began both to do', 'Connection of Works and Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the works of Jesus and their significance. Acts 1:1 refers to all that Jesus began to do and teach, while John 10:32-38 highlights the good works Jesus performed as evidence of his divine authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 1, 43, 18, 19, 21, 'all that Jesus began both to do and teach', 'Teaching and Public Discourse', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' public teaching. Both passages emphasize Jesus'' openness in sharing his doctrine, as seen in ''all that Jesus began both to do and teach'' and ''I ever taught in the synagogue''.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 1, 44, 2, 22, 22, 'all that Jesus began both to do', 'Connection of Jesus'' Actions', 'This connection highlights the continuity of Jesus'' actions and teachings. Acts 1:1 mentions what Jesus began to do, while Acts 2:22 emphasizes the miracles and signs he performed, showcasing his divine approval.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 2, 44, 1, 9, 9, 'he was taken up', 'Ascension of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the event of Jesus'' ascension. Acts 1:2 mentions his being taken up, while Acts 1:9 describes the moment he was taken up and received by a cloud.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 2, 23, 59, 20, 21, 'through the Holy Ghost had given commandments', 'Connection of Spirit and Commandments', 'This connection highlights the role of the Holy Spirit in guiding the apostles, paralleling the promise of God''s spirit in Isaiah. Both passages emphasize the importance of divine instruction and the enduring presence of God''s words.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 2, 43, 20, 21, 21, 'commandments unto the apostles', 'Sending of the Apostles', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus empowering his apostles. In Acts, Jesus gives commandments through the Holy Ghost, while in John, he sends them as he was sent by the Father.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 2, 44, 10, 38, 38, 'through the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Holy Ghost in Jesus'' ministry. Acts 1:2 mentions the Holy Ghost giving commandments, while Acts 10:38 highlights Jesus being anointed with the Holy Ghost.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 2, 58, 9, 24, 24, 'taken up', 'Ascension and Christ''s Presence', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s ascension and His presence in heaven. Acts 1:2 mentions His being taken up, while Hebrews 9:24 emphasizes His appearance in the presence of God.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 2, 43, 13, 18, 18, 'whom he had chosen', 'Chosen Apostles and Betrayal', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being ''chosen.'' Acts 1:2 refers to the apostles whom Jesus had chosen, while John 13:18 highlights the knowledge of betrayal among those chosen. This connection highlights the tension between selection and betrayal.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 2, 40, 28, 19, 20, 'commandments unto the apostles', 'Connection of Commandments and Teaching', 'This connection highlights the continuity of Jesus'' commandments to his apostles and the directive to teach all nations. Both passages emphasize the importance of following the teachings given by Jesus through the Holy Ghost.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 3, 46, 15, 5, 7, 'being seen of them forty days', 'Resurrection Appearances of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' post-resurrection appearances. Both passages emphasize the various individuals and groups who witnessed Jesus alive after his passion.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 3, 44, 13, 31, 31, 'being seen of them forty days', 'Witnesses of the Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of witnesses who saw Jesus after his resurrection. Acts 1:3 mentions that he was seen for forty days, while Acts 13:31 refers to those who witnessed him after his return from Galilee.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 3, 43, 20, 26, 26, NULL, 'Resurrection Appearances of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' post-resurrection appearances. Acts 1:3 mentions Jesus showing himself alive for forty days, while John 20:26 describes a specific appearance to the disciples, emphasizing his continued presence among them.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 3, 62, 1, 1, 1, 'being seen of them forty days', 'Connection of Witness and Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of witnessing the resurrected Christ. Both passages emphasize the physical experience of seeing and handling Jesus, affirming His reality and the message of eternal life.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 3, 43, 21, 1, 1, 'he shewed himself alive', 'Post-Resurrection Appearances of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus showing himself alive to the disciples after his resurrection. Acts mentions he was seen for forty days, while John describes a specific appearance at the sea of Tiberias.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 3, 40, 28, 9, 9, 'shewed himself alive after his passion', 'Resurrection Appearance of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus showing himself alive after his resurrection. Acts 1:3 mentions Jesus being seen for forty days, while Matthew 28:9 describes an encounter where Jesus meets his followers, affirming his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 3, 40, 21, 43, 43, 'kingdom of God', 'Connection of the Kingdom of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of the kingdom of God being central to both passages. Acts 1:3 mentions Jesus speaking of ''the things pertaining to the kingdom of God,'' while Matthew 21:43 discusses the kingdom being given to a nation that produces its fruits.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 4, 42, 24, 49, 49, 'the promise of the Father', 'Promise of the Father', 'Both passages emphasize the command to wait in Jerusalem for the promise of the Father, highlighting the importance of this instruction before receiving power from on high.', 'theme', 0.566, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 4, 43, 14, 16, 16, 'the promise of the Father', 'Promise of the Comforter', 'This connection highlights the promise of the Father in Acts 1:4 and the Comforter mentioned in John 14:16. Both passages emphasize the assurance of divine presence and guidance for the believers.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 4, 43, 15, 26, 26, 'promise of the Father', 'Promise of the Spirit', 'This connection highlights the promise of the Holy Spirit in both passages. Acts 1:4 refers to the ''promise of the Father,'' which aligns with John 15:26''s mention of the ''Comforter'' sent from the Father.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 4, 42, 12, 12, 12, 'the promise of the Father', 'Promise of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine guidance. In Acts 1:4, the promise of the Father relates to the Holy Spirit, while Luke 12:12 emphasizes the Holy Ghost teaching in specific moments.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 4, 44, 2, 33, 33, 'the promise of the Father', 'Promise of the Holy Ghost', 'This connection highlights the promise of the Father mentioned in Acts 1:4, which is fulfilled in Acts 2:33 when the Holy Ghost is shed forth. Both passages emphasize the significance of waiting for and receiving this divine promise.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 4, 40, 10, 20, 20, 'the promise of the Father', 'Connection of Divine Guidance', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine guidance through the Holy Spirit. In Acts, the promise of the Father refers to the Holy Spirit, while in Matthew, the Spirit of the Father speaks through believers.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 4, 44, 10, 41, 41, 'promise of the Father', 'Promise and Witness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine promise and witness. In Acts 1:4, the promise of the Father is emphasized, while Acts 10:41 speaks of chosen witnesses who experienced the risen Christ, fulfilling that promise.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 5, 40, 3, 11, 11, 'baptized with the Holy Ghost', 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of baptism with the Holy Ghost. Acts 1:5 references this baptism as a future event, while Matthew 3:11 presents it as a promise from one who is mightier, linking the two ideas.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 5, 44, 11, 15, 16, NULL, 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the transition from John''s water baptism to the baptism with the Holy Ghost. Acts 11:15-16 recalls the promise made in Acts 1:5, linking the two events.', 'quotation', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 5, 42, 3, 16, 16, 'baptized with the Holy Ghost', 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of baptism with the Holy Ghost, linking John''s water baptism to a greater spiritual baptism that Jesus will provide. This connection highlights the transition from physical to spiritual baptism.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 5, 46, 12, 13, 13, 'baptized with the Holy Ghost', 'Baptism by the Spirit', 'This connection highlights the theme of baptism in the Holy Spirit. Both passages emphasize the transformative experience of being baptized, first mentioned in Acts and further elaborated in 1 Corinthians as a unifying act among believers.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 5, 56, 3, 5, 5, 'baptized with the Holy Ghost', 'Connection of Baptism and Renewal', 'This connection highlights the theme of baptism and the Holy Spirit. Both passages emphasize the transformative work of the Holy Ghost in believers, linking water baptism with spiritual regeneration.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 5, 41, 1, 8, 8, 'baptized with the Holy Ghost', 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the transition from water baptism to baptism with the Holy Ghost. This connection highlights the significance of the Holy Spirit in the believer''s experience following John''s ministry.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 5, 44, 2, 1, 4, 'baptized with the Holy Ghost', 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'This connection highlights the fulfillment of John''s prophecy about being baptized with the Holy Ghost. In Acts 1:5, the promise is made, and in Acts 2:1-4, the actual event occurs as the disciples are filled with the Holy Ghost.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 6, 42, 19, 11, 11, 'restore again the kingdom to Israel', 'Expectation of God''s Kingdom', 'Both passages emphasize the anticipation of the kingdom of God. In Acts, the disciples inquire about the restoration of the kingdom to Israel, while in Luke, the people believe the kingdom should appear immediately.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 6, 42, 17, 20, 20, 'kingdom to Israel', 'Kingdom of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the kingdom. Acts 1:6 asks about restoring the kingdom to Israel, while Luke 17:20 discusses the nature of the kingdom of God.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 6, 27, 7, 27, 27, 'restore again the kingdom to Israel', 'Kingdom Restoration Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of the kingdom being restored to Israel in Acts, paralleling the promise of an everlasting kingdom in Daniel. Both passages emphasize the significance of God''s kingdom and its dominion over all nations.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 6, 40, 24, 3, 3, 'wilt thou at this time restore again the kingdom to Israel?', 'Disciples'' Questions on Kingdom', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' inquiries about the kingdom and the end times. They reflect a shared concern for understanding God''s timeline and restoration.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 6, 26, 37, 24, 27, 'restore again the kingdom to Israel', 'Restoration of the Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of restoration in both passages. Acts 1:6 expresses the disciples'' hope for the restoration of the kingdom to Israel, while Ezekiel 37:24-27 speaks of David as king and the establishment of an everlasting covenant, indicating a future restoration of Israel under God''s rule.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 6, 23, 9, 6, 7, 'wilt thou at this time restore again the kingdom to Israel?', 'Kingdom Restoration Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of the kingdom''s restoration. Acts 1:6 asks about restoring the kingdom to Israel, while Isaiah 9:6-7 speaks of a government established on the throne of David.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 6, 24, 23, 5, 6, 'wilt thou at this time restore again the kingdom to Israel', 'Restoration of the Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of restoration and kingship. In Acts, the disciples inquire about the restoration of the kingdom to Israel, which parallels Jeremiah''s prophecy of a righteous King who will reign and bring salvation to Judah and Israel.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 7, 40, 24, 36, 36, 'the times or the seasons', 'Knowledge of Times and Seasons', 'Both passages emphasize that knowledge of specific times is reserved for the Father alone. Acts 1:7 states it is not for the disciples to know, while Matthew 24:36 affirms that no one knows the day or hour except the Father.', 'theme', 0.566, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 7, 52, 5, 1, 2, 'times or the seasons', 'Connection of Times and Seasons', 'This connection highlights the theme of times and seasons in both passages. Acts 1:7 states it is not for the disciples to know these times, while 1 Thessalonians 5:1-2 indicates that the believers are already aware of the coming day of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.552, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 7, 41, 13, 32, 32, 'times or the seasons', 'Knowledge of Times and Seasons', 'Both passages emphasize the limitation of human knowledge regarding divine timing. Acts 1:7 states it is not for humans to know the times, while Mark 13:32 asserts that no one knows the day or hour.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 7, 5, 29, 29, 29, NULL, 'Understanding Divine Secrets', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of secret knowledge belonging to God. Acts 1:7 highlights that certain times are under God''s authority, while Deuteronomy 29:29 states that secret things belong to the Lord, suggesting a shared theme of divine sovereignty over knowledge.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 7, 41, 10, 40, 40, NULL, 'Authority Over Divine Timing', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority over specific roles and timings. Both passages emphasize that certain matters, such as times and positions of honor, are determined by the Father and not by human desire.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 7, 27, 2, 21, 21, 'times or the seasons', 'Divine Control Over Times', 'This connection highlights God''s sovereignty over times and seasons in both passages. Acts 1:7 emphasizes that knowledge of these times is reserved for the Father, while Daniel 2:21 states that God changes the times and seasons.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 7, 49, 1, 10, 10, 'times or the seasons', 'Connection of Times and Seasons', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine timing. Acts 1:7 emphasizes that knowledge of times is reserved for the Father, while Ephesians 1:10 speaks of the ''fulness of times'' in God''s plan for gathering all things in Christ.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 8, 40, 28, 19, 19, 'ye shall be witnesses unto me', 'Commission to Witness and Baptize', 'Both passages emphasize the call to spread the message of Jesus. Acts 1:8 highlights being witnesses, while Matthew 28:19 focuses on teaching and baptizing all nations.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 8, 41, 16, 15, 15, 'witnesses unto me both in Jerusalem', 'Connection of Witnessing and Preaching', 'Both passages emphasize the call to spread the gospel. Acts 1:8 mentions being ''witnesses'' in all the earth, while Mark 16:15 commands to ''go...into all the world'' and preach.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 8, 45, 15, 19, 19, 'both in Jerusalem', 'Witnessing and Gospel Preaching', 'Both passages emphasize the spread of the gospel starting from Jerusalem. Acts 1:8 mentions being witnesses in Jerusalem, while Romans 15:19 references preaching the gospel from Jerusalem.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 8, 44, 4, 33, 33, 'ye shall receive power', 'Power and Witness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of power given to the apostles. Both passages emphasize the role of the apostles as witnesses, with Acts 1:8 mentioning receiving power and Acts 4:33 describing the apostles giving witness with great power.', 'theme', 0.958, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 8, 44, 5, 32, 32, 'witnesses unto me', 'Witnesses and the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the role of witnesses empowered by the Holy Ghost. Acts 1:8 speaks of receiving power to be witnesses, while Acts 5:32 affirms the apostles as witnesses alongside the Holy Ghost.', 'theme', 0.9159999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 8, 42, 24, 46, 49, 'ye shall be witnesses unto me', 'Witnesses and Power Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the disciples as witnesses, beginning in Jerusalem and extending to all nations. They also highlight the promise of receiving power from the Holy Spirit to fulfill this mission.', 'theme', 0.825, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 8, 45, 10, 18, 18, 'uttermost part of the earth', 'Witnessing to the Ends of the Earth', 'Both passages emphasize the spread of the message of Jesus to all nations. Acts 1:8 mentions being witnesses ''unto the uttermost part of the earth,'' while Romans 10:18 refers to their sound going ''unto the ends of the world.''', 'theme', 0.671, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 9, 27, 7, 13, 13, 'a cloud received him out of their sight', 'Connection of Cloud Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of clouds in significant moments involving the Son of Man. In Acts, a cloud receives Jesus, while in Daniel, he comes with the clouds of heaven.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 9, 42, 24, 50, 51, 'was taken up', 'Ascension of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the moment of Jesus'' ascension into heaven. They describe how he was taken up and parted from the disciples, highlighting the miraculous nature of this event.', 'parallel', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 9, 41, 16, 19, 19, NULL, 'Ascension of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the ascension of Jesus into heaven. Acts 1:9 describes Him being taken up and received by a cloud, while Mark 16:19 states He was received up into heaven and sat at God''s right hand.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 9, 2, 19, 9, 9, 'a cloud received him', 'Divine Presence in Clouds', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine presence associated with clouds. In both passages, a cloud signifies God''s communication and presence, first in Exodus with Moses and then in Acts with Jesus'' ascension.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 9, 43, 6, 62, 62, NULL, 'Ascension of the Son of Man', 'Both passages emphasize the ascension of Jesus. Acts 1:9 describes his ascension into a cloud, while John 6:62 anticipates seeing him ascend to his previous position.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 9, 44, 1, 2, 2, 'he was taken up', 'Ascension of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the event of Jesus being ''taken up.'' Acts 1:2 refers to the day he was taken up, while Acts 1:9 describes the moment itself, linking the two accounts of his ascension.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 9, 49, 4, 8, 12, NULL, 'Ascension and Gifts Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of ascension in both passages. Acts 1:9 describes Jesus'' ascension, while Ephesians 4:8 refers to his ascension and the gifts he gives to men.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 10, 42, 24, 4, 4, 'two men stood by them', 'Angelic Presence in Ascension', 'Both passages emphasize the appearance of two men in shining garments at significant moments of Jesus'' ascension. This connection highlights the role of angels in conveying messages during pivotal events.', 'parallel', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 10, 43, 20, 12, 12, 'two men stood by them in white apparel', 'Angels in White Apparel', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of two angels in white. In Acts, the angels appear as men in white apparel, while in John, they are described as sitting in white. This connection highlights the role of angels in significant resurrection and ascension events.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 10, 41, 16, 5, 5, 'two men stood by them in white apparel', 'Angelic Appearances in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the presence of angelic figures in both passages. In Acts, two men in white apparel appear, while in Mark, a young man in a white garment is encountered.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 10, 66, 7, 14, 14, 'white apparel', 'White Apparel and Purity', 'This connection highlights the theme of purity and righteousness, as both passages mention individuals in white apparel. In Acts, the two men in white represent a divine presence, while in Revelation, those who have washed their robes signify purification through the sacrifice of the Lamb.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 10, 27, 7, 9, 9, 'two men stood by them in white apparel', 'Heavenly Beings in White Apparel', 'This connection highlights the presence of heavenly beings in both passages. In Acts, the two men in white apparel appear as Jesus ascends, while in Daniel, the Ancient of Days is described with a white garment, emphasizing the divine and majestic nature of these figures.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 10, 40, 17, 2, 2, 'white apparel', 'Connection of White Apparel', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of figures in white. In Acts, the two men are described as wearing white apparel, while in Matthew, Jesus'' raiment is white as the light.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 10, 40, 28, 3, 3, 'two men stood by them in white apparel', 'Angelic Appearances in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of beings in white apparel, suggesting a divine or heavenly connection. The description of the men in white in Acts parallels the angelic figure in Matthew, highlighting their roles in significant events.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 11, 66, 1, 7, 7, 'this same Jesus, which is taken up', 'Return of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the promise of Jesus'' return in both passages. Acts 1:11 speaks of Jesus coming back in the same manner as he ascended, while Revelation 1:7 describes his coming with clouds, emphasizing visibility and recognition.', 'theme', 0.517, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 11, 52, 4, 16, 16, 'this same Jesus, which is taken up from you into heaven, shall so come in like manner', 'Connection of Christ''s Return', 'Both passages emphasize the return of Jesus from heaven. Acts 1:11 states He will come back in like manner, while 1 Thessalonians 4:16 describes His descent from heaven.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 11, 41, 13, 26, 26, 'this same Jesus, which is taken up', 'Connection of Christ''s Return', 'Both passages emphasize the return of Jesus. Acts 1:11 speaks of Jesus coming back in the same manner as He ascended, while Mark 13:26 describes Him coming in the clouds with power and glory.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 11, 43, 14, 3, 3, 'this same Jesus, which is taken up', 'Return of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the promise of Jesus'' return. Acts 1:11 speaks of Jesus coming back in the same manner as He ascended, while John 14:3 assures believers that He will come again to receive them.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 11, 40, 24, 30, 30, 'this same Jesus, which is taken up', 'Connection of Jesus'' Return', 'Both passages emphasize the coming of Jesus in the clouds. Acts 1:11 states he shall come in like manner, while Matthew 24:30 describes him coming in the clouds with power and glory.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 11, 40, 25, 31, 31, 'this same Jesus, which is taken up', 'Return of Jesus in Glory', 'This connection highlights the promise of Jesus'' return. Both passages emphasize the manner of His coming, with Acts noting He will return as He ascended, and Matthew describing His glorious arrival.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 1, 11, 27, 7, 13, 14, 'this same Jesus, which is taken up', 'Connection of Jesus'' Return', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' return with clouds, as seen in both passages. Acts 1:11 mentions Jesus coming back in like manner, while Daniel 7:13 describes one like the Son of man coming with the clouds of heaven.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
